    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-07T06:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-07T06:54:00-05:00" n="729"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.515/76: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moose</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-07T15:00:00+03:06"
                            >January 7, 1944—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:51 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. The second 2 million riyals minted in England mentioned in Department’s 113,
                    December 20, 10 p.m.,<note n="39" xml:id="d729fn39">
                        <ref target="frus1943v04#pg_919">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 919</ref>.</note> arrived here January
                    5, and were delivered to Finance Minister<note n="40" xml:id="d729fn40">Abdullah
                        Suleiman.</note> against temporary receipt. Preparation of final receipts
                    awaits Treasury certification of quantity of silver used. Legation already has
                    such certification from London and Bombay mints.</p>
                <p>Responsible officials indicate that further quantities of Lend-Lease silver will
                    be requested in 1944 but that accurate determination of requirements awaits
                    agreement between local and British authorities about disposition of pilgrimage
                    “tariff items” now on deposit in sterling funds outside Saudi Arabia. See also
                    my 5, January 7, 2 p.m.</p>
                <p>Any developments will be promptly reported.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moose</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
